---
const facts = ['Seed first', 'Replace any layer', 'Fork and own it'];

const layers = [
  ['Seed layer', 'GalexC starts from galexc-starter-pack, likely soon galexc-seed, which establishes the foundational interaction model and working system.'],
  ['Interaction layer', 'Durable sessions, tasks, async dispatch, scheduled work, workstation Pi, and intercom create the first serious operating surface.'],
  ['Services', 'Storage, search, routing, notifications, and background services provide continuity and visibility.'],
  ['Replaceable implementation', 'Postgres, Python services, schedulers, and other internals are defaults, not commandments. Swap them if your system wants something else.'],
  ['Personal evolution', 'Once forked, the stack becomes your own professional-grade personal AI environment rather than a centrally maintained product.'],
];

const surfaces = [
  ['Seed', 'Start from a coherent base instead of assembling every primitive from scratch.'],
  ['Adapt', 'Replace or reshape infrastructure, services, and workflows to fit your own needs.'],
  ['Operate', 'Build a real cadence with your AI so the system stays useful, maintained, and personal over time.'],
];

const sequence = ['Start from seed', 'Learn the surfaces', 'Replace what you want', 'Build your cadence', 'Own the system'];
---

<div class="essay-page architecture-page">
  <section class="page-hero-note-grid">
    <div>
      <p class="eyebrow">System</p>
      <h1 class="page-display-title">How GalexC is arranged</h1>
      <p class="page-lede">
        GalexC begins with a seed system. Today that is galexc-starter-pack, and it
        will likely become galexc-seed. The point is not to lock you into my exact
        stack forever. The point is to establish the foundational elements of a
        professional-grade personal AI system: durable interaction layers, tasks,
        async dispatches, scheduled tasks, a workstation Pi environment aligned with
        dispatched agents, and core communications like intercom. From there, you
        take it wherever you want.
      </p>
    </div>
    <ul class="page-note-list">
      {facts.map((fact) => <li>{fact}</li>)}
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="page-module page-module-panel architecture-plate">
    <p class="eyebrow">System at a glance</p>
    <div class="architecture-bands">
      {
        layers.map(([title, body], index) => (
          <div class:list={['architecture-band', index === layers.length - 1 && 'architecture-band-active']}>
            <p class="architecture-band__title">{title}</p>
            <p>{body}</p>
          </div>
        ))
      }
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-grid-three">
    {
      surfaces.map(([title, body]) => (
        <article class="page-module page-module-panel surface-card">
          <p class="eyebrow">System motion</p>
          <h2>{title}</h2>
          <p>{body}</p>
        </article>
      ))
    }
  </section>

  <section class="page-module">
    <div class="module-heading-row">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">One path through the system</p>
        <h2 class="page-section-title">Start coherent, then diverge deliberately</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="page-caption">The seed is the beginning, not the boundary.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="workflow-ribbon">
      {
        sequence.map((step, index) => (
          <>
            <div class="workflow-ribbon__step">{step}</div>
            {index < sequence.length - 1 && <div class="workflow-ribbon__connector" aria-hidden="true"></div>}
          </>
        ))
      }
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-grid-two">
    <article class="page-module">
      <p class="eyebrow">Why the system starts this way</p>
      <p>
        The seed gives you a coherent philosophy and a working substrate before you
        begin customizing. That makes the system teachable. It lets you learn how to
        interact with your personal AI before you decide which parts to keep, replace,
        or extend. If you want my learnings and features through Parley, you can use
        them. You do not need to. The system is designed so optional inheritance never
        overrides actual ownership.
      </p>
    </article>
    <aside class="page-module page-module-panel legend-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Legend</p>
      <ul class="legend-card__list">
        <li><strong>Seed layer</strong> - the initial system that establishes GalexC's core philosophy</li>
        <li><strong>Surface cards</strong> - the three motions that matter: start, adapt, operate</li>
        <li><strong>Workflow ribbon</strong> - the path from coherent foundation to owned personal system</li>
      </ul>
    </aside>
  </section>
</div>
